			<pb n="1"/>
				<p>Mr Editor</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">In your <date>April</date> number&#44; there appears<lb/> a communication&#44; from <placeName>California</placeName> over the signature of<lb/> &#8220;<hi rend="underline"><persName>Theophilus</persName></hi>&#8221; relating to affairs in that distant part of<lb/> the Union&#44; which from his statement appears to be every<lb/> thing but what they should be&#44; Among other things he<lb/> <del>says</del> avers that &#8220;<persName>Dr. Henry</persName> then refused to make more proselytes&#44;&#8221;<lb/> and then <del>proceeds and</del> continues says &#8220;Two <add>Hebrew</add> applied to the Congre&#61;<lb/>&#61;gation Shearith Israel to be married to widows having<lb/> no children&#44; which <persName>Dr Henry</persName> refused to do&#44; as he<lb/> stated that the widows must have <add>Hebrew</add>.&#8221;</p>
				<p>And after continuing his bill of complaints in the same<lb/> style&#44; finished by envoking your attention &#8220;to the right<lb/> minded Israelites of <placeName><sic>Calafernia</sic></placeName>&#8221; Which you in a very kind<lb/> and Philanthropic manner proceed so to do&#44; much no doubt&#44;<lb/> to your own satisfaction&#44; but perhaps without that strict<lb/> <sic>reguard</sic> to the law which the question required.  Where do<lb/> you find any such a law as &#8220;The marriage of the two  <add>Hebrew</add> is illegal.&#8221;<lb/>  Certainly not in the Even Haezer V 1 the place quoted by<lb/> you in your <hi rend="underline">note</hi>&#44; and sir could you find it in any<lb/> other place&#44; perhaps not&#44; and not content with simply<lb/> answering the question propounded&#44; you say &#8220;it would be the same if<lb/> simple Israelites&#8221; Now no such a law as that can be found<lb/> in any book of standard authority among any Israelitish<lb/> authors in the known world&#44; and why and for what</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>purpose do you answer &#8220;the right minded&#8221; people<lb/> in that manner&#44; when you know&#44; if you know any<lb/> thing about the matter at all&#44; that in the way the case<lb/> was stated&#44; that there could be no objection to the marriage<lb/> of the widows to the two <add>Hebrew</add> or to any other two Israelites.</p>
				<p>&#8220;That a <persName>Cohen</persName> is prohibited from marrying a <hi rend="underline">Chabuzah</hi>&#8221;<lb/> as stated by you&#44; with reference to the Iben Heazer V.1<lb/> is a most singular thing&#44; for the word <hi rend="underline">Chabuzah</hi> is not<lb/> mentioned in that place and as to the word&#44; perhaps you<lb/> would have done much better in your &#8220;Note&#8221; if you had<lb/> told the &#8220;right minded&#8221; correctly where it is to be found<lb/> or what is the meaning of the word&#44; but Mr Editor<lb/> things both in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> and <placeName>California</placeName> appear to<lb/> be much out of place&#44; in one place a <hi rend="underline">Dr</hi> refuses &#8220;to make<lb/> any <hi rend="underline">more</hi> proselytes&#8221; while in the other an Editor refers<lb/> to places and laws not to be found&#44; and writes about<lb/> a &#8220;Chabuzah&#8221; which puts all his numerous readers on<lb/> tip toe of expectation hoping that in his next number<lb/> <del>that</del> he will tell them where the law is to be found which<lb/> forbids a childless widow from being married without <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> and the meaning of the word Chabuzah.</p>
			<p rend="indent(12)"><persName role="author">S. A.</persName></p>
				<p>Private</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Can you insert the above in <date>May</date> No</p>
